<h1><center>Lecture 1: Course Sneak Preview, Equidecomposing Polygons</center></h1>

Today's lecture was mostly spent on course policies and an overview of all assignments.  The main topic of instruction came from one of the possible final projects on "Equidecomposability."  We showed a constructive proof that for two polygons <b>A</b> and <b>B</b> with the same area, it is possible to cut <b>A</b> into a finite number of pieces that can be rigidly re-arranged like a puzzle to form polygon <b>B</b>.  This is known as the <a href = "http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Wallace%E2%80%93Bolyai%E2%80%93Gerwien_theorem">Wallace Bolyai Gerwein theorem</a>.







